article.description: The Washington Mystics didn't have a winning season in their first five years. Now they'll play for the Eastern Conference title.
article.headline: Mystics' fortunes have changed rapidly
article.linkText: Mystics reach East finals by finishing off Sting
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- As Washington's bus pulled away, headed
off to the Eastern Conference finals, a few dozen Mystics fans
surrounded it -- cheering the team's recent turnaround.

	   The players smiled and waved, soaking in the excitement of their
first winning season in the Mystics' six years.

	   The Mystics beat Charlotte 62-59 Saturday to complete a two-game
sweep of the Sting in the Eastern Conference semifinals.

	   Washington was 10-22 last season.

	   "It feels great, just great,'' said Chamique Holdsclaw,
Washington's star forward. "To see all these Mystics fans who
probably made a 6-hour drive down from D.C. to support us, it
really makes us feel good.

	   "We'll celebrate tonight, get it out of our systems and then
focus on the next round.''

	   Washington will play the winner of the Indiana-New York series
for a spot in the WNBA Finals.

	   The Sting, meanwhile, will wait to see what its fate is in
Charlotte.

	   Last year's conference champions have been a lame-duck franchise
since the NBA's Hornets moved to New Orleans this summer and the
WNBA assumed control of the team. Their existence in Charlotte
hinges largely on the city's bid to land an expansion NBA team.

	   "I'm looking forward to coming back to Charlotte next year -- I
can't fathom playing anywhere else,'' guard Allison Feaster said.

	   Coco Miller, the WNBA's most improved player this season, scored
21 points and led Washington down the stretch.

	   Miller, whose twin sister, Kelly, is a reserve for the Sting,
paved the way for Washington when the Sting put their clamps on
Holdsclaw by scoring 12 points in a decisive 14-6 run.

	   After Charlotte took a 53-48 lead, Coco Miller hit a 3-pointer
then picked off a pass and converted it into a fast-break layup
that tied the game with 6:56 left.

	   Her 3-pointer about 4 minutes later gave Washington the lead for
good and she added a pair of free throws with 8 seconds left.

	   "I just saw a lot of shot opportunities,'' Coco Miller said.
"I did not second-guess passing them up and had enough confidence
to shoot them and knock them down.''

	   Holdsclaw said Charlotte's zone forced Miller to step forward.

	   "They tried to close it down inside and when that happens, it
sucks the defense in,'' Holdsclaw said. "So you have to look to
hit the open player and that was Coco, and she hit some huge shots
for us.''

	   Holdsclaw, the WNBA's leading scorer, had 15 points and 11
rebounds, and Stacey Dales-Schuman added 12 points.

	   Andrea Stinson led Charlotte with 14 points, but was scoreless
in the second half. Tonya Edwards added 11, Charlotte Smith 10.

	   Feaster had a career-high 12 rebounds for the Sting, but was
held scoreless on 0-for-8 shooting.

	   "We're extremely disappointed that the season has come to an
end,'' Charlotte coach Anne Donovan said. "I feel like we did not
accomplish our goals.''

	   When the game was over, the Washington players ran to the seats
behind their bench to celebrate with the hundreds of fans on hand
to support them.

	   Both Millers were first-round picks in the 2001 WNBA draft,
Kelly taken by Charlotte with the second overall pick, and Coco
selected ninth by Washington.

	   "She's capable of playing the way she did, she really hurt us
and she played very well,'' said Kelly Miller, who plans to root
for the Mystics the rest of the season. "I have to support my
sister.''

	   But they were rivals in this game, especially on a play late in
the first half.

	   Holdsclaw stepped in front of Kelly Miller's lob pass to Tammy
Sutton-Brown and intercepted the ball near Charlotte's basket.

	   Holdsclaw tossed it to halfcourt, where Coco Miller caught it
and scored on a fast-break layup that drew a foul from her sister.
Kelly Miller slapped her hands together in disgust, while Coco and
Holdsclaw exchanged high-fives.

	   "I'm really excited about the game and how well we played,''
Coco Miller said. "I'm just really proud of our team.''
